Posted: Fri Apr 20, 2012 5:51 am
I brewed my second 5-gallon batch last night. It was pretty uneventful. I stuck my top-up water (2.5 gallon poland spring jug) in the fridge a few hours before I brewed; the combination of that + the cold water in the tub was enough to drop the wort to 100* (similar to last time). I would've liked to get it lower, but it was getting late (10:30) and I just wanted to be done with it. I left it overnight (lid on!) and it was at 80* this morning, so I pitched the yeast after re-hydrating. this weekend I am definitely either making or buying a wort chiller and buying some tubing to match the autosiphon (I got 1/2" tubing with the kit, I think the autosiphon needs 7/16").I've been using the gas stove in my kitchen and doing partial (2.5 gallon) boils and it's getting frustrating to take so long to bring the water up to temperature - fortunately I have a propane burner, so I'm going to use that for the next batch (which won't be for a while, since I've got 10 gallons fermenting!). I might try a cider next. My beer accoutrements are starting to take up nearly as much space as my cycling gear.Quote:Also interesting, apparently most of the soft copper tubing is refrigerant grade, which is allowed to contain lead, cadmium, arsenic, all sorts of fun stuff. I guess to be food safe you need C12200 alloy, or one of the various potable water certifications. At Lowes, the cheapest brand, JMF, ended up being the one to go with. I called their customer service line, they answered the phone right away, and I read the SKU to them over the phone and they told me which ones were C12200. Very cool customer service, so thumbs up to them, and the guy at Lowes who helped me track down all the mis-shelved variants. 20' of 1/4" copper acquired for just under $14.I wonder why the stuff at mcmaster is so much more - a 10' coil of 1/4" alloy 122 is $42.
