Frennzy wrote:AFAIK, you have to send them out to be tested. Most people just use published averages for each rhizome.Or they don't use them as bittering hops.It looks like I might be able to get them tested for <$30, so that's a possibility - but I strongly suspect I simply won't get around to it.What kind of range do you expect to see within a varietal? I've always just gone by what my local brew shop lists as the content; I've never really compared one season's crop to another. If we're talking about the difference between 6 and 7 AAU, then I don't care. With as slipshod an operation as I run, that won't even be close to the least precise part of the brew. If we're talking about 4 to 8 AAU, though, even I'll have to care.Although I suppose just not using them as bittering hops is a workable solution. I admit to being somewhat enthralled with the idea of increasing the "home" part of "homebrew," but it really wouldn't be such a big deal to keep several ounces of (say) Galena on hand just for baseline bittering.I probably won't be able to resist at least one brew with the Centennial for bittering and the Cascade for finishing, though.
