Posted: Sun Apr 29, 2012 3:42 pm
Quote:1) The kit's estimated OG was 1.043, but my hydrometer reading came in closer to 1.039. Is that likely to be a problem? Any idea what I might have done wrong to cause that?Do you know how much water really boiled off? Quote:2) The wort was really foamy after pouring it into the bucket, even before stirring it or adding the yeast. I assume that normal, but the instructions didn't really mention it.I'd say it's normal - and good, at this point - plenty of oxygen for the yeast to work with. most instructions I've seen recommend pouring back and forth between vessels or vigorous stirring to introduce enough oxygen prior to fermentation.Quote:3) The dry yeast pack says it will basically be done fermenting in 2-3 days. However, the kit says to leave it in the fermenter for 1-2 weeks. What's the best practice here? Leave it in for the full 2 weeks? Bottle after 1 week?bottle after hydrometer readings stabilize. My bavarian wheat was pretty stable after 4 days but I'm still giving it two weeks before I even think about doing anything with it. I didn't keep track of the irish red but it had a week or two in primary and it'll have two weeks in secondary.Quote:Next upgrade that I'm seeing a need for is a thief. I used a sanitized turkey baster to fill the tube the hydrometer came in, but that didn't really work as smoothly as I would have liked. I'm finding the same need - using a baster sucks. I'm starting to wish I had gone for a larger pot - I went for 32qt, which is fine for a full boil of an extract brew (which I'll be doing as soon as I pick up the hand-me-down propane burner), but I'd like to move to BIAB all-grain pretty soon and it seems like 40qts is really in order for that.
